---
import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import HelpfulTools from '../components/HelpfulTools.astro';
---

<MainLayout
  title={"Turning 65 in Utah | Medicare Roadmap | AltaMedicare"}
  description={"Step-by-step Medicare timeline for turning 65: enrollment periods, employer coverage, HSA issues, avoiding lifetime late penalties."}
  canonical="/turning-65.html"
>

<section class="page-header">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="index.html">Home</a> &nbsp;&rsaquo;&nbsp; Turning 65</div>
    <h1>Turning 65? Here&rsquo;s Your Medicare Roadmap</h1>
    <p class="lede">Aging into Medicare can feel overwhelming. Here&rsquo;s a calm, step-by-step timeline to help you avoid penalties and make the right choice.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-tinted">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">Step by step</span>
      <h2>Your Medicare Timeline</h2>
      <p>The most important window is the 7-month Initial Enrollment Period around your 65th birthday. Here&rsquo;s what to do, when.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <span class="age">6+ Months Before 65</span>
          <h4>Start Learning</h4>
          <p>Begin researching your options. If you&rsquo;re still working with employer coverage, find out whether to keep it, drop it, or coordinate with Medicare. <a href="contact.html">A free consultation now</a> can save penalties later.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <span class="age">3 Months Before 65</span>
          <h4>Initial Enrollment Period Begins</h4>
          <p>Your 7-month IEP starts. This is when you can enroll in Part A, Part B, and a Medicare plan (Advantage or Supplement + Part D). Earlier enrollment means coverage that starts the month you turn 65.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <span class="age">Birthday Month</span>
          <h4>You&rsquo;re Eligible</h4>
          <p>Medicare coverage can begin on the first of your birthday month if you enroll early. We&rsquo;ll have your plan locked in well before this date.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <span class="age">3 Months After 65</span>
          <h4>IEP Closes</h4>
          <p>Your Initial Enrollment Period ends. Missing this window can trigger lifetime Part B and Part D late penalties unless you have qualifying coverage from elsewhere (like an active employer plan).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <span class="age">Year After Year</span>
          <h4>Annual Reviews</h4>
          <p>Plans change every year. We do a free annual review during the Annual Enrollment Period (Oct 15&ndash;Dec 7) to make sure your plan still fits your medications, doctors, and budget.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-white">
  <div class="container content-narrow">
    <h2>Common Turning-65 Situations</h2>

    <h3>Still Working with Employer Coverage</h3>
    <p>If you (or your spouse) have <strong>creditable coverage</strong> from a current employer with 20+ employees, you may be able to delay Part B without penalty. We&rsquo;ll help you decide whether keeping employer coverage, switching to Medicare, or coordinating both is best for your situation.</p>

    <h3>You Have an HSA</h3>
    <p>This one trips a lot of people up. Once you enroll in any part of Medicare, you can no longer contribute to a Health Savings Account. If you&rsquo;re still working and contributing to an HSA, plan your Medicare timing carefully.</p>

    <h3>COBRA, Retiree Coverage, or VA</h3>
    <p>None of these count as &ldquo;creditable coverage&rdquo; for Part B purposes the way active employer coverage does. If you&rsquo;re relying on these, you almost always need to enroll in Part B at 65 to avoid penalties.</p>

    <h3>You&rsquo;re On Social Security Already</h3>
    <p>If you&rsquo;re already drawing Social Security, you&rsquo;ll be auto-enrolled in Part A and Part B when you turn 65. You should still review your options &mdash; auto-enrollment doesn&rsquo;t mean you have the best plan for prescriptions or other benefits.</p>

    <h2>Penalties to Avoid</h2>
    <h3>Part B Late Enrollment Penalty</h3>
    <p>If you don&rsquo;t enroll in Part B when first eligible (and don&rsquo;t have qualifying coverage), your premium increases 10% for every full 12-month period you could have had Part B but didn&rsquo;t. This penalty stays with you for life.</p>

    <h3>Part D Late Enrollment Penalty</h3>
    <p>If you go more than 63 days without creditable drug coverage, you&rsquo;ll owe a Part D penalty &mdash; 1% of the national base premium for every month you went without it. Also lifetime.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Good news: these penalties are entirely avoidable.</strong>
      <p style="margin:8px 0 0;">A 30-minute conversation now is all it takes to map out the right timing for your situation. <a href="contact.html">Schedule your free consultation &rarr;</a></p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="final-cta">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Have Questions? Let's Talk.</h2>
    <p>One free, no-pressure call &mdash; clear answers, no sales pitch.</p>
    <div class="cta-buttons">
      <a href="contact.html" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">Schedule Consultation</a>
      <a href="tel:4352925548" class="btn btn-outline btn-lg">Call (435) 292-5548</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<HelpfulTools />

</MainLayout>
